00:34:02,269 --> 00:34:05,071
JACKEE: And third place goes to...

775
00:34:06,640 --> 00:34:09,475
our bronze beauties, The Amazonians!

776
00:34:09,510 --> 00:34:11,511
(crowd cheering)

777
00:34:14,815 --> 00:34:16,115
Are you all right, Mr. Shue?

778
00:34:16,150 --> 00:34:17,483
You never looked this nervous before.

779
00:34:17,518 --> 00:34:19,552
Yeah, just, uh...

780
00:34:19,586 --> 00:34:22,188
there's a lot riding on it this time.

781
00:34:22,222 --> 00:34:24,490
And now the pivotal moment is here.

782
00:34:24,525 --> 00:34:28,528
For there can only be one
champion show choir per nation.

783
00:34:31,899 --> 00:34:34,867
JACKEE: Second place goes to...

784
00:34:43,744 --> 00:34:46,145
(gasps)... New Directions!

785
00:34:46,180 --> 00:34:48,915
Which means the winner of the
National Show Choir Championship

786
00:34:48,949 --> 00:34:50,883
is Throat Explosion!

787
00:34:50,918 --> 00:34:52,885
(crowd cheering)

788
00:34:52,920 --> 00:34:54,921
♪ ♪

789
00:35:39,089 --> 00:35:41,590
So Jean-Baptiste mailed it here?

790
00:35:41,625 --> 00:35:43,092
Yeah, he said that when he found out

791
00:35:43,126 --> 00:35:45,261
one of the people on his
team stole it, he was furious.

792
00:35:45,295 --> 00:35:47,763
Then he apologized and
said that he made sure

793
00:35:47,798 --> 00:35:49,698
that the thief was kicked off the team.

794
00:35:49,733 --> 00:35:52,401
Huh. A bully with a moral code.

795
00:35:52,435 --> 00:35:55,805
All right, guys, time to put
our new trophy in the case.

796
00:35:55,839 --> 00:35:57,840
I've always found that
second place trophies

797
00:35:57,874 --> 00:35:59,975
are just a lasting reminder
that you didn't win.

798
00:36:00,010 --> 00:36:01,277
WILL: Hey, there were

799
00:36:01,311 --> 00:36:02,611
16 teams in that competition.

800
00:36:02,646 --> 00:36:04,647
We beat 14 of the best

801
00:36:04,681 --> 00:36:05,848
show choirs in the country.

802
00:36:05,882 --> 00:36:07,216
I'm sorry we let him down.

803
00:36:08,418 --> 00:36:10,953
Let who down? Finn?

804
00:36:11,822 --> 00:36:12,988
We just really wanted

805
00:36:13,023 --> 00:36:14,857
to win this one for him, and for you.

806
00:36:14,891 --> 00:36:17,026
We had a plan that we were
gonna call you up on stage

807
00:36:17,060 --> 00:36:18,194
and give you the trophy to keep.

808
00:36:18,228 --> 00:36:19,695
It's not right.

809
00:36:19,729 --> 00:36:22,131
This is not how the
story was supposed to end.

810
00:36:22,165 --> 00:36:23,432
You're right.

811
00:36:23,467 --> 00:36:26,268
Oh, it would have burned Finn
to have lost to those guys.

812
00:36:26,303 --> 00:36:28,637
All we would have heard for months was

813
00:36:28,672 --> 00:36:30,139
how the judges had robbed you

814
00:36:30,173 --> 00:36:32,541
or how you were so much better than them.

815
00:36:32,576 --> 00:36:34,310
BURT: But then he would have stood up

816
00:36:34,344 --> 00:36:36,345
and he would have told you that even though

817
00:36:36,379 --> 00:36:40,149
most of you had never been in
a show choir before this year,

818
00:36:40,183 --> 00:36:44,120
you still stood tall
against the best of the best.

819
00:36:44,210 --> 00:36:46,077
And you know what? Even though Finn

820
00:36:46,112 --> 00:36:48,680
didn't have the best
voice or the best rhythm

821
00:36:48,714 --> 00:36:50,248
or the best throwing arm,

822
00:36:50,283 --> 00:36:55,086
he always brought out the best in himself

823
00:36:55,121 --> 00:36:57,455
and in others, and the
great thing about him is

824
00:36:57,490 --> 00:37:00,926
he always managed to find
a way to feel like he'd won.

825
00:37:02,461 --> 00:37:04,563
I was really proud of you guys up there.

826
00:37:04,597 --> 00:37:06,665
Hearing those songs was so healing for me.

827
00:37:06,699 --> 00:37:10,335
And... I don't know... I
saw how much he meant to you.

828
00:37:10,369 --> 00:37:14,506
So, win or lose, he lives in you guys.

829
00:37:16,175 --> 00:37:18,476
WILL: Okay, guys.

830
00:37:18,511 --> 00:37:21,179
Let's put this trophy where it belongs.

831
00:37:21,213 --> 00:37:22,647
ARTIE: A second place showing

832
00:37:22,682 --> 00:37:25,817
is superior to when Finn decided
to make out with Rachel onstage

833
00:37:25,851 --> 00:37:27,352
and we ended up in 12th.

834
00:37:29,021 --> 00:37:32,090
Principal Sue wants to see you, Schuester.

835
00:37:38,631 --> 00:37:40,632
Dead man walking.

836
00:37:50,775 --> 00:37:52,744
SUE: Well, Roz, I got to admit,

837
00:37:52,778 --> 00:37:54,646
I didn't think you had it in you.

838
00:37:54,680 --> 00:37:57,716
Between the toxic fumes from
your excessive beauty products

839
00:37:57,750 --> 00:37:59,618
and all those MoonPies I see you

840
00:37:59,652 --> 00:38:01,119
shame-eating in the bathroom stalls

841
00:38:01,153 --> 00:38:02,520
when you don't think anyone's looking,

842
00:38:02,555 --> 00:38:04,556
I didn't think there was room

843
00:38:04,590 --> 00:38:06,891
for the kind of fire and creativity it took

844
00:38:06,926 --> 00:38:08,560
to uphold the Cheerios! honor

845
00:38:08,594 --> 00:38:11,062
and bring home another
national championship.

846
00:38:11,097 --> 00:38:13,665
I'm sure it gives you
great disappointment to know

847
00:38:13,699 --> 00:38:17,936
you weren't the only reason the
Cheerios! won all of those years.

848
00:38:17,970 --> 00:38:19,604
Come back when you've won 16 more

849
00:38:19,639 --> 00:38:21,539
and had a child with a celebrity crooner.

850
00:38:21,574 --> 00:38:23,608
Then you can talk trash, Roz.

851
00:38:24,744 --> 00:38:26,311
Until then, as principal...

852
00:38:26,345 --> 00:38:27,812
Are they almost done?

853
00:38:27,847 --> 00:38:30,949
She'll get to you when
she gets to you, loser.

854
00:38:30,983 --> 00:38:32,617
I... second place is not losing.

855
00:38:32,652 --> 00:38:34,419
It's like winning a silver
medal in the Olympics.

856
00:38:34,453 --> 00:38:35,620
Sure, if there was

857
00:38:35,655 --> 00:38:38,790
an Olympic event in being totally gay.

858
00:38:38,824 --> 00:38:39,925
ROZ: Whoa.

859
00:38:39,959 --> 00:38:42,627
Just like my date with John Salley.

860
00:38:42,662 --> 00:38:44,296
(chuckling)

861
00:38:44,330 --> 00:38:45,430
Well, bye, all.

862
00:38:45,464 --> 00:38:46,698
If you need me over the summer,

863
00:38:46,732 --> 00:38:50,035
you can reach me at my beach
cottage in Saint-Tropez.

864
00:38:50,836 --> 00:38:52,103
But there ain't no phones.

865
00:38:52,138 --> 00:38:53,104
(chuckles)

866
00:38:53,139 --> 00:38:54,272
(humming)

867
00:38:54,307 --> 00:38:55,440
Come on in, William.

868
00:38:56,475 --> 00:38:58,977
(sighs softly)

869
00:39:05,451 --> 00:39:08,119
I bet you're hoping for
a last-minute reprieve

870
00:39:08,154 --> 00:39:11,456
and that I'll say something
about how your plucky band

871
00:39:11,490 --> 00:39:15,260
of pinhead minstrels overcame
so much to get where they did

872
00:39:15,294 --> 00:39:19,464
and how second place is
actually an achievement.

873
00:39:19,498 --> 00:39:22,701
I... I can't say I wasn't secretly
hoping you would consider it.

874
00:39:22,735 --> 00:39:24,202
I have considered it.

875
00:39:24,237 --> 00:39:26,171
More than you know.

876
00:39:26,205 --> 00:39:27,939
But I just can't.

877
00:39:27,974 --> 00:39:30,775
In the words of ex-Principal Figgins,

878
00:39:30,810 --> 00:39:33,111
my hands are tied.

879
00:39:34,313 --> 00:39:36,281
I'm the principal now, William,

880
00:39:36,315 --> 00:39:39,084
and my job is concerned with
the health of the entire school,

881
00:39:39,118 --> 00:39:41,019
not just the fiefdoms that I like.

882
00:39:41,053 --> 00:39:42,687
And I do like you, William.

883
00:39:42,722 --> 00:39:44,856
That's why I'm so mean to you.

884
00:39:45,758 --> 00:39:47,325
That being said,

885
00:39:47,360 --> 00:39:50,195
the Cheerios! stay because they won.

886
00:39:50,229 --> 00:39:52,197
So does the debate team, the football team,

887
00:39:52,231 --> 00:39:53,732
the girls soccer team

888
00:39:53,766 --> 00:39:55,200
and mock U.N.

889
00:39:55,234 --> 00:39:57,102
However, diving,

890
00:39:57,136 --> 00:39:59,938
academic decathlon, actual decathlon

891
00:39:59,972 --> 00:40:03,808
and, yes, the glee club need to go.

892
00:40:08,347 --> 00:40:10,295
Should I fight?

893
00:40:10,304 --> 00:40:13,740
Sh... should I make a
speech about the arts or...

894
00:40:13,819 --> 00:40:16,588
or how much this club
means to me personally?

895
00:40:16,622 --> 00:40:17,589
No, no.

896
00:40:17,623 --> 00:40:19,057
Save that for your wife.

897
00:40:19,091 --> 00:40:21,393
It'd probably turn her on.

898
00:40:21,517 --> 00:40:24,552
That won't make any difference here.

899
00:40:24,587 --> 00:40:26,287
So this is really it.

900
00:40:28,357 --> 00:40:29,691
What's gonna happen to the choir room?

901
00:40:29,725 --> 00:40:30,959
Well, it's prime real estate.

902
00:40:30,993 --> 00:40:33,628
I'll probably turn it into two classrooms.

903
00:40:33,663 --> 00:40:36,965
And since we won't be
needing the band anymore

904
00:40:36,999 --> 00:40:39,467
to play everything from obscure Broadway

905
00:40:39,502 --> 00:40:41,403
to Queen at a moment's notice,

906
00:40:41,437 --> 00:40:43,004
probably sell off their equipment

907
00:40:43,039 --> 00:40:44,773
and buy some computers.

908
00:40:46,342 --> 00:40:48,176
Butt chin up, Schuester.

909
00:40:48,210 --> 00:40:49,778
Look where you were

910
00:40:49,812 --> 00:40:52,380
four years ago when you started this thing.

911
00:40:52,415 --> 00:40:54,382
You've got a national championship trophy

912
00:40:54,417 --> 00:40:56,051
from last year in that case

913
00:40:56,085 --> 00:40:58,687
and a bunch of other loser
trophies standing with it.

914
00:40:58,721 --> 00:41:01,489
You and your team have
done phenomenally well,

915
00:41:01,524 --> 00:41:04,292
and you did it with the
world's greatest nemesis

916
00:41:04,327 --> 00:41:06,361
playing her best game against you.

917
00:41:08,097 --> 00:41:10,065
You didn't lose, William.

918
00:41:12,101 --> 00:41:14,536
The game is just over.

919
00:41:25,281 --> 00:41:27,582
- Oh, my God.
- SANTANA: Now what?

920
00:41:27,616 --> 00:41:29,718
Your band booked a huge gig playing a show

921
00:41:29,752 --> 00:41:31,319
at the Union Square subway station?

922
00:41:31,354 --> 00:41:33,421
Why do you want to know? So
you can steal his dream, too?

923
00:41:33,456 --> 00:41:34,856
- Exactly.
- It's Glee Club.

924
00:41:34,890 --> 00:41:36,091
They've been disbanded.

925
00:41:36,125 --> 00:41:37,892
They didn't win at
nationals; they're turning

926
00:41:37,927 --> 00:41:39,961
the choir room into a
computer lab or something.

